## Purpose
This project applies linear algebra concepts and dimensionality reduction techniques using Python. Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and t-SNE are used to reduce high-dimensional data and visualize patterns. The Iris dataset is used for simplicity and clarity. Ethical considerations related to dimensionality reduction are also discussed.

### Import Libraries
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.datasets import load_iris
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE

# Load and scale data
iris = load_iris()
X, y = iris.data, iris.target
labels = iris.target_names
X_scaled = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)

# PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)
print("Explained variance ratios:", pca.explained_variance_ratio_)

plt.figure()
for i in range(len(labels)):
plt.scatter(X_pca[y==i,0], X_pca[y==i,1], label=labels[i])
plt.xlabel("PC1")
plt.ylabel("PC2")
plt.title("PCA of Iris")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# t-SNE
X_tsne = TSNE(n_components=2, random_state=42, perplexity=30).fit_transform(X_scaled)
plt.figure()
for i in range(len(labels)):
plt.scatter(X_tsne[y==i,0], X_tsne[y==i,1], label=labels[i])
plt.xlabel("t-SNE1")
plt.ylabel("t-SNE2")
plt.title("t-SNE of Iris")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Notes:
* PCA preserves global variance; t-SNE preserves local structure.
* t-SNE shows clearer clusters visually; PCA gives interpretable variance metrics.

Ethical Reflection:
Dimensionality reduction may introduce bias by removing features important for certain groups. Visualization choices, like t-SNE exaggerating separation, can mislead interpretation. Including diverse perspectives in feature selection helps ensure fairness and reduces potential bias.
